<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="528" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,536,1031]" pageId="9" pageNumber="528">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,536,562]" pageId="9" pageNumber="528">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Small or medium-sized moths. The sexual dimorphism is more expressed in the generic complex (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 11–18" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1877,1901]" captionTargetBox="[184,1420,183,1828]" captionTargetId="figure-27@6.[151,1436,181,1854]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 11–18. Zadadra spp.: adults. Depositories of the specimens: 11 in OUMNH; 12 in NHMUK (© The Trustees of the Natural History Museum); 13–18 in MWM/ZSM." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4745239" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4745239/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="528">Figs 11–18</figureCitation>
). The male forewing is shorter and broader than that of female, its distal part is slightly curved posteriorly, and the anal and outer margins are convex. Additionally, the forewing cell of the male is narrow and bearing a longitudinal row of androconial scales continuing to the basal part of the area between the veins Cu 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1311,1319,662,676]" fontSize="6" pageId="9" pageNumber="528">1</subScript>
and M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1405,1429,662,676]" fontSize="6" pageId="9" pageNumber="528">2–3</subScript>
. The male hindwing is conspicuously broader than that of female and bearing a wide dark area of androconial scales at the costa (the character unique among the genera of the generic complex). The female forewing is long and narrow, nearly straight. The male genitalia of the genus (
<figureCitation box="[862,993,752,778]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 27–30" captionStart-1="FIGURES 31–32" captionStartId-0="12.[151,264,1944,1968]" captionStartId-1="13.[151,264,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox-0="[159,1423,181,1909]" captionTargetBox-1="[153,1408,186,1884]" captionTargetId-0="figure-27@12.[151,1436,181,1920]" captionTargetId-1="figure-19@13.[151,1436,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId-0="12" captionTargetPageId-1="13" captionText-0="FIGURES 27–30. Zadadra spp.: male genitalia. Depositories of the specimens: 27 in OUMNH; 28–30 in MWM/ZSM." captionText-1="FIGURES 31–32. Zadadra spp.: male genitalia. The specimens are deposited in MWM/ZSM." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4745253" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4745257" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/4745253/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/4745257/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="528">Figs 27–32</figureCitation>
) are characterized by the combination of the following diagnostic characters: (1) the juxta is narrow, weakly sclerotized, its distal end is connected to the intervalval commissura by a membrane; (2) the intervalval commissura is thick membranous with a weakly sclerotized medial area, connecting from one third to a half of valvae (an autapomorphic feature); (3) the cucullus is weakly sclerotized, well-separated from the distal saccular process; (4) the sacculus is heavily sclerotized, wide, lobe-like (an autapomorphic feature); (5) the distal saccular process is short but broad, robust, without setae. The female genitalia of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moore" authorityYear="1878" box="[365,461,968,994]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Zadadra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="528" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[365,461,968,994]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="528">Zadadra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[475,601,968,994]" captionStart="FIGURES 33–38" captionStartId="14.[151,264,1703,1727]" captionTargetBox="[154,1431,186,1644]" captionTargetId="figure-27@14.[151,1436,181,1679]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 33–38. Lithosiina spp.: female genitalia. Depositories of the specimens: 33 and 36 in NHMUK (© The Trustees of the Natural History Museum); 34 and 38 in CKC; 35 and 37 in MWM/ZSM." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4745261" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4745261/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="528">Figs 37, 38</figureCitation>
) display no remarkable differences from those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dubatolov, Volynkin &amp; Kishida" authorityYear="2018" box="[1153,1246,968,994]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Chinasa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="528" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1153,1246,968,994]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="528">Chinasa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1261,1341,968,995]" captionStart="FIGURES 33–38" captionStartId="14.[151,264,1703,1727]" captionTargetBox="[154,1431,186,1644]" captionTargetId="figure-27@14.[151,1436,181,1679]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 33–38. Lithosiina spp.: female genitalia. Depositories of the specimens: 33 and 36 in NHMUK (© The Trustees of the Natural History Museum); 34 and 38 in CKC; 35 and 37 in MWM/ZSM." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4745261" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4745261/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="528">Fig. 35</figureCitation>
) but can be distinguished by the presence of sclerotized pockets on the 7th sternite (absent in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dubatolov, Volynkin &amp; Kishida" authorityYear="2018" box="[1098,1191,1004,1030]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Chinasa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="528" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1098,1191,1004,1030]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="528">Chinasa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
